      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "In a serious academic context, presenting the trickle-down theory as an equally weighted counterpoint to empirical evidence of increased inequality is methodologically weak. Economists are increasingly treating the trickle-down argument as a theoretical model rather than a validated prediction, given the consistent data showing wealth concentration. Instead of presenting it as an equal side, it is more accurate to frame it as a hypothesis that has been repeatedly challenged by real-world outcomes.",
      "source": "target",
